1
00:00:20,276 --> 00:00:23,116
>> IAN FISCH: Good morning, and
welcome to Accessibility on iOS,


2
00:00:23,386 --> 00:00:25,626
my name is Ian Fisch
and I'm an engineer


3
00:00:25,626 --> 00:00:27,056
on the Accessibility team.


4
00:00:28,576 --> 00:00:31,866
So accessibility is really
about making sure all users,


5
00:00:32,195 --> 00:00:34,916
regardless of abilities,
have full access to all


6
00:00:34,916 --> 00:00:37,516
of our products and the great
features you put in your apps,


7
00:00:37,996 --> 00:00:40,726
and that means we get to
focus on users and think


8
00:00:40,726 --> 00:00:43,686
about how users with these
different abilities use


9
00:00:43,686 --> 00:00:44,296
our features.


10
00:00:44,846 --> 00:00:47,636
That, in turn, has allowed
Apple to create great futures


11
00:00:47,946 --> 00:00:51,336
to empower users, like
the girl you see here


12
00:00:51,336 --> 00:00:55,106
with a switch mounted next
to her head which allows her


13
00:00:55,106 --> 00:00:57,646
to control all of iOS,
with just that one button.


14
00:00:57,646 --> 00:01:01,016
And that gives her the
freedom to communicate and play


15
00:01:01,436 --> 00:01:02,756
without the need for assistance.


16
00:01:04,226 --> 00:01:07,366
And as users get older
and older, more and more


17
00:01:07,366 --> 00:01:09,696
of them will be using these
accessibility features,


18
00:01:09,696 --> 00:01:12,116
so the time is really
now to start thinking


19
00:01:12,116 --> 00:01:15,306
about accessibility in
the terms of your app.


20
00:01:16,336 --> 00:01:19,806
So Apple creates these great
accessibility features,


21
00:01:19,806 --> 00:01:21,376
but that's only part
of the story.


22
00:01:21,696 --> 00:01:24,016
We need all of your
apps to be accessible


23
00:01:24,396 --> 00:01:27,146
so we can create a great
ecosystem for accessibility


24
00:01:27,146 --> 00:01:28,426
and empower these users.


25
00:01:29,886 --> 00:01:32,276
Today we will be talking about
the accessibility futures


26
00:01:32,566 --> 00:01:33,906
that Apple provides on iOS.


27
00:01:33,906 --> 00:01:39,416
We will look at what's new
in iOS ,9 and we will go


28
00:01:39,416 --> 00:01:41,166
through what we call
an accessibility audit,


29
00:01:41,246 --> 00:01:42,536
where we will look at an app


30
00:01:42,536 --> 00:01:44,376
and see how accessible
it is already.


31
00:01:45,166 --> 00:01:48,236
Then we will go through
implementing some accessibility


32
00:01:48,646 --> 00:01:49,226
in that app.


33
00:01:50,596 --> 00:01:52,476
But first, let's take a look


34
00:01:52,476 --> 00:01:55,376
at the accessibility
features that Apple provides.


35
00:01:56,136 --> 00:02:00,516
We break those into four large
areas: hearing, learning,


36
00:02:01,386 --> 00:02:03,626
vision, and physical and motor.


37
00:02:04,126 --> 00:02:06,676
So I will go through just a few
of the features that we have,


38
00:02:06,676 --> 00:02:10,985
but there are many more I don't
have time to talk about today.


39
00:02:11,156 --> 00:02:13,926
For hearing, we have
made-for-iPhone hearing aids,


40
00:02:14,306 --> 00:02:17,296
which allow users to stream
high-quality audio directly


41
00:02:17,296 --> 00:02:19,756
from their iOS device
and control the settings


42
00:02:19,756 --> 00:02:20,596
of those hearing aids.


43
00:02:21,146 --> 00:02:24,516
This replaces a lot of extra
hardware the user would have


44
00:02:24,516 --> 00:02:25,716
to carry with them
all of the time


45
00:02:26,086 --> 00:02:30,486
and provides a much more private
experience for setting these


46
00:02:30,926 --> 00:02:32,246
or changing the settings
for hearing aids.


47
00:02:33,756 --> 00:02:37,336
For learning, we have guided
access, which lets teachers,


48
00:02:37,376 --> 00:02:41,506
parents, and caregivers remove
distractions so users can focus


49
00:02:41,506 --> 00:02:42,966
on a specific app or task.


50
00:02:43,956 --> 00:02:46,476
And we even provide time limits


51
00:02:46,676 --> 00:02:49,656
so you can restrict the
time allowed in a task.


52
00:02:50,076 --> 00:02:54,056
For developers, we provide
an API that allows you


53
00:02:54,056 --> 00:02:57,506
to provide specific
restrictions for your app.


54
00:02:58,876 --> 00:03:03,316
For vision, we have
VoiceOver, which lets blind


55
00:03:03,316 --> 00:03:05,306
and low-vision users
touch the screen


56
00:03:05,306 --> 00:03:07,346
and have VoiceOver read
what's under their finger.


57
00:03:07,896 --> 00:03:11,036
So they can use gestures
to interact


58
00:03:11,036 --> 00:03:14,356
with the touchscreen even though
they can't see the screen.


59
00:03:16,116 --> 00:03:19,966
We also have Zoom, which lets
users who may need things


60
00:03:19,966 --> 00:03:21,186
to be just a little bit bigger


61
00:03:21,186 --> 00:03:25,206
but can see the screen magnify
the interface of your app


62
00:03:25,426 --> 00:03:27,476
and the operating system.


63
00:03:27,936 --> 00:03:31,066
And it will even
follow text as you type


64
00:03:31,066 --> 00:03:32,686
and leave the keyboard unzoomed


65
00:03:33,216 --> 00:03:35,476
so you can still have full
access to the keyboard.


66
00:03:35,906 --> 00:03:38,106
Finally for vision, we
have Vision Accommodations,


67
00:03:38,496 --> 00:03:40,086
which adjusts the
interface for users


68
00:03:40,086 --> 00:03:42,966
who might need larger
text, higher contrast,


69
00:03:43,386 --> 00:03:46,586
or reduced motion so users can
more easily orient themselves


70
00:03:46,586 --> 00:03:47,486
with what's on screen.


71
00:03:49,236 --> 00:03:51,686
For physical and motor,
we have Switch Control,


72
00:03:51,686 --> 00:03:54,356
which uses these
switches, or large buttons,


73
00:03:54,806 --> 00:03:56,346
to control the operating system.


74
00:03:56,476 --> 00:03:59,296
It's great for users who may
not be able to fully interact


75
00:03:59,296 --> 00:04:01,626
with the touchscreen,
and it allows them


76
00:04:01,626 --> 00:04:04,076
to sequentially navigate
the items on screen


77
00:04:04,426 --> 00:04:07,386
and perform complex
gestures and even play games.


78
00:04:08,216 --> 00:04:14,296
If a user has difficulty
performing gestures


79
00:04:14,296 --> 00:04:16,326
or pressing a physical
button, we have AssistiveTouch,


80
00:04:16,416 --> 00:04:19,375
which provides a menu to
quickly access recorded gestures


81
00:04:19,935 --> 00:04:21,065
and hardware buttons.


82
00:04:21,065 --> 00:04:21,726
And this even works


83
00:04:21,726 --> 00:04:24,376
with third-party assistive
devices like wheelchairs.


84
00:04:25,066 --> 00:04:29,256
And brand new in iOS 9 we
have Touch Accommodations,


85
00:04:29,646 --> 00:04:32,196
which helps users who may have
difficulty performing precise


86
00:04:32,196 --> 00:04:35,766
gestures by changing the way the
touchscreen responds to touches,


87
00:04:36,866 --> 00:04:38,766
and I would love to give
you a demo of that now.


88
00:04:40,336 --> 00:04:42,386
Like all accessibility
features, you can turn


89
00:04:42,386 --> 00:04:45,086
on Touch Accommodations by
going to Settings, General,


90
00:04:45,556 --> 00:04:48,506
Accessibility, and you
can see the large list


91
00:04:48,506 --> 00:04:50,106
of accessibility
features we provide.


92
00:04:50,636 --> 00:04:53,296
But for now, we will go
into Touch Accommodations.


93
00:04:54,026 --> 00:04:55,416
And you see we have
got three options.


94
00:04:56,006 --> 00:04:57,366
Let's look at Hold Duration.


95
00:04:58,196 --> 00:05:02,936
And this allows people
who may have tremors


96
00:05:02,936 --> 00:05:06,526
and touch the screen more than
they would like to set a timeout


97
00:05:06,846 --> 00:05:11,126
so not all touches are used.


98
00:05:11,126 --> 00:05:14,536
So let's turn on Hold Duration
and Touch Accommodations.


99
00:05:14,786 --> 00:05:17,106
So I go back to the Home
button, you will notice


100
00:05:17,106 --> 00:05:20,486
when I put my finger on the
screen I get this timer icon,


101
00:05:20,536 --> 00:05:23,116
and if I lift up
before the time is up,


102
00:05:23,646 --> 00:05:25,266
the touch isn't passed
to the icon.


103
00:05:25,646 --> 00:05:28,456
But if I tap and hold
for the whole duration,


104
00:05:29,866 --> 00:05:33,076
it will open the app.


105
00:05:33,196 --> 00:05:37,536
So if I have tremors, they
won't be respected as touches.


106
00:05:38,376 --> 00:05:41,586
Great! So if we go
back into Settings,


107
00:05:42,356 --> 00:05:48,406
we can look at Tap Assistance,
which is great for users


108
00:05:48,406 --> 00:05:52,446
who may not be able to land
on exactly the right icon


109
00:05:52,446 --> 00:05:53,456
that they are looking for.


110
00:05:54,146 --> 00:05:56,256
So if we go back
to the Home screen,


111
00:05:57,236 --> 00:06:02,306
you can see that if I press on
Clock and then move to Calendar,


112
00:06:02,926 --> 00:06:05,956
the touch will be passed to
Calendar instead of Clock.


113
00:06:06,446 --> 00:06:09,966
So it's the final touch
location that's respected.


114
00:06:10,576 --> 00:06:18,256
And that's Touch
Accommodations on iOS 9.


115
00:06:18,516 --> 00:06:22,256
So, many of these accessibility
features rely on UIAccessibility


116
00:06:22,486 --> 00:06:25,196
to bridge the gap between
the assistive technology


117
00:06:25,346 --> 00:06:26,246
and your app.


118
00:06:26,916 --> 00:06:30,646
For instance, if a VoiceOver
user taps on the screen,


119
00:06:31,076 --> 00:06:33,256
it will look for the
element under their finger


120
00:06:33,836 --> 00:06:36,706
and ask the element in your app
for its accessibility label.


121
00:06:37,276 --> 00:06:40,736
So when you return the string
Weather, VoiceOver will speak:


122
00:06:40,936 --> 00:06:41,836
>> VOICEOVER: Weather.


123
00:06:42,696 --> 00:06:46,036
>> IAN FISCH: And similarly
with Switch Control,


124
00:06:46,036 --> 00:06:49,536
the Switch Control user
brings up the menu on one


125
00:06:49,536 --> 00:06:51,406
of your elements,
will ask that element


126
00:06:51,466 --> 00:06:53,626
for its accessibility
custom actions,


127
00:06:54,246 --> 00:06:56,836
and when you return the
actions -- move, pass and trade,


128
00:06:56,996 --> 00:06:57,916
if it's a game app, maybe --


129
00:06:57,916 --> 00:07:00,246
it will display those in
the Switch Control menu


130
00:07:00,656 --> 00:07:03,766
so users have fast
access to these actions


131
00:07:04,166 --> 00:07:05,256
on elements in your app.


132
00:07:06,096 --> 00:07:09,586
So you will notice that
UIAccessibility is really


133
00:07:09,586 --> 00:07:11,916
about asking questions
of elements in your app


134
00:07:12,316 --> 00:07:15,226
so the assistive technology
knows how to work with it.


135
00:07:16,236 --> 00:07:17,616
So let's go through a
few of those questions.


136
00:07:18,286 --> 00:07:19,936
The first one is: Do
I serve a purpose?


137
00:07:20,666 --> 00:07:24,336
This is really about
whether an element is useful


138
00:07:24,336 --> 00:07:25,656
or important to the user.


139
00:07:25,936 --> 00:07:28,196
So a line that separates
elements


140
00:07:28,196 --> 00:07:29,806
in a view is very
important visually,


141
00:07:30,066 --> 00:07:31,846
but since the user
can't interact with it


142
00:07:31,846 --> 00:07:34,736
and it doesn't provide
information like a UI label,


143
00:07:35,176 --> 00:07:36,726
it's not really serving
a purpose.


144
00:07:37,926 --> 00:07:40,916
So we answer this question
with Is Accessibility Element.


145
00:07:41,566 --> 00:07:45,496
If we look at the Plus button
in Clock, it's a button,


146
00:07:45,496 --> 00:07:46,946
the user can interact with it,


147
00:07:46,946 --> 00:07:48,986
and so for that we
would return True.


148
00:07:49,536 --> 00:07:53,526
The next most important
question is: What's my name?


149
00:07:53,986 --> 00:07:56,146
We answer that with
Accessibility Label.


150
00:07:56,246 --> 00:07:58,976
This is what VoiceOver
uses to read


151
00:07:58,976 --> 00:08:00,606
to the user what's
under their finger.


152
00:08:01,386 --> 00:08:05,586
If we look at the Plus
button, you might be tempted


153
00:08:05,586 --> 00:08:08,386
to set the label to something
like Button To Add A Clock,


154
00:08:09,026 --> 00:08:12,216
which is a great description
of what the button will do,


155
00:08:12,216 --> 00:08:14,726
but you should think of the
accessibility label more


156
00:08:14,726 --> 00:08:16,626
like the title of a button,


157
00:08:16,626 --> 00:08:20,366
so a better accessibility
label would just be Add.


158
00:08:21,276 --> 00:08:25,986
So what's the personality
of the element in your app?


159
00:08:25,986 --> 00:08:29,566
And this is really about
describing to the user


160
00:08:29,706 --> 00:08:32,696
and the assistive technology
how they can interact


161
00:08:32,696 --> 00:08:33,275
with an element.


162
00:08:33,645 --> 00:08:35,696
So we answer that with
Accessibility Traits.


163
00:08:35,946 --> 00:08:38,905
So we have a whole host
of traits that you can set


164
00:08:38,905 --> 00:08:42,056
on elements that describe
how to interact with them.


165
00:08:42,546 --> 00:08:46,076
So if we look at the Plus
or Add button in Clock,


166
00:08:46,576 --> 00:08:49,476
we would set the trait to
Button, because it's a button,


167
00:08:49,476 --> 00:08:52,026
and VoiceOver would read
it as a button to the user.


168
00:08:52,536 --> 00:08:56,306
Next question is:
What's my value?


169
00:08:56,716 --> 00:08:59,666
So if an element has a state
that changes frequently


170
00:08:59,666 --> 00:09:02,506
over its life, we would
change that or update


171
00:09:02,506 --> 00:09:04,636
that with Accessibility Value.


172
00:09:05,486 --> 00:09:07,926
So if this time we look
at the Clock element,


173
00:09:08,426 --> 00:09:10,186
the value that changes
would be the time,


174
00:09:10,746 --> 00:09:15,156
and so we would return the
string 11:20 a.m. and update


175
00:09:15,156 --> 00:09:16,626
that accordingly as
the time changes.


176
00:09:17,286 --> 00:09:21,936
So the next question is: How
should people interact with me?


177
00:09:21,936 --> 00:09:26,496
If the traits aren't enough
to describe how to interact


178
00:09:26,496 --> 00:09:28,306
with an element, where you
need just a little bit more


179
00:09:28,306 --> 00:09:31,466
information, you can provide
that with Accessibility Hint.


180
00:09:32,636 --> 00:09:35,306
So if we look at the
grabber in World Clock,


181
00:09:35,846 --> 00:09:37,946
we could set the hint to
something like, drag up


182
00:09:37,946 --> 00:09:39,136
or down to change the order.


183
00:09:39,766 --> 00:09:41,406
And this is, this describes


184
00:09:41,406 --> 00:09:43,326
to the user exactly how
they can interact with it,


185
00:09:43,606 --> 00:09:47,706
just a short description
of how to use it.


186
00:09:47,986 --> 00:09:49,396
And finally: Where am I?


187
00:09:49,896 --> 00:09:51,556
You may have noticed
that Switch Control


188
00:09:51,786 --> 00:09:54,866
and VoiceOver have cursors
that move around the screen.


189
00:09:55,516 --> 00:09:57,476
So we need to know where
to display that cursor.


190
00:09:58,036 --> 00:10:00,026
So we answer that with
Accessibility Frame.


191
00:10:01,116 --> 00:10:03,766
And that's how we draw the
beautiful cursor we see here.


192
00:10:04,756 --> 00:10:07,356
It's important to
remember that the frame is


193
00:10:07,356 --> 00:10:09,696
in screen coordinates, so
we provide a helper method


194
00:10:09,696 --> 00:10:11,536
to convert from view
to screen coordinates.


195
00:10:12,556 --> 00:10:16,106
Most of the time we assume this
to just be the frame of a view,


196
00:10:16,516 --> 00:10:18,846
so you won't need to touch
this unless you need it


197
00:10:18,846 --> 00:10:20,776
to be something a
little bit more specific.


198
00:10:21,436 --> 00:10:24,526
And that's it!


199
00:10:24,876 --> 00:10:28,756
Those six methods make up the
basic API for UI accessibility,


200
00:10:29,126 --> 00:10:31,646
and that's enough to get
most of accessibility done,


201
00:10:32,126 --> 00:10:34,926
so just a few lines of
code and a few minutes


202
00:10:35,126 --> 00:10:36,706
to make your app
really accessible.


203
00:10:37,196 --> 00:10:41,536
But the really great news
is we do most of the work.


204
00:10:41,766 --> 00:10:44,716
So if you use standard
controls in UIKit,


205
00:10:45,146 --> 00:10:46,476
most of this is done for you.


206
00:10:47,056 --> 00:10:48,656
If you do custom drawing,


207
00:10:48,996 --> 00:10:50,976
we need you to answer
these questions for us


208
00:10:51,206 --> 00:10:54,456
so accessibility users can know
how to interact with your app.


209
00:10:54,456 --> 00:10:57,136
So just that really
small investment


210
00:10:57,446 --> 00:11:00,266
of those six methods will
give you a large reward


211
00:11:00,266 --> 00:11:02,286
of a lot more people being
able to use your app.


212
00:11:03,086 --> 00:11:06,776
So it's not that much to
make something accessible.


213
00:11:07,386 --> 00:11:11,586
So now your convinced:
accessibility, just six methods,


214
00:11:11,866 --> 00:11:13,886
that's easy, how do I do it?


215
00:11:14,566 --> 00:11:16,706
The first step is
design for accessibility.


216
00:11:17,116 --> 00:11:19,956
So when you are thinking
about your app and thinking


217
00:11:19,956 --> 00:11:22,796
about how users will use
the app you are building,


218
00:11:22,906 --> 00:11:24,866
think about Switch
Control and VoiceOver users


219
00:11:25,326 --> 00:11:27,346
and how they will
interact with your app.


220
00:11:28,666 --> 00:11:32,076
But if you have an app already,
like we assume most of you do,


221
00:11:32,586 --> 00:11:34,836
the best way to start is
do an audit of your app


222
00:11:34,836 --> 00:11:37,886
and see how accessible it is
already, because, like I said,


223
00:11:37,986 --> 00:11:40,226
if you use UIKit
standard controls,


224
00:11:40,296 --> 00:11:41,666
most of this should
be done already.


225
00:11:42,826 --> 00:11:45,476
There are a few ways to
do an accessibility audit.


226
00:11:46,046 --> 00:11:48,216
The first one is the
accessibility inspector


227
00:11:48,706 --> 00:11:49,816
in the simulator.


228
00:11:50,256 --> 00:11:52,586
And you turn that on by
going to Settings, General,


229
00:11:52,986 --> 00:11:56,036
Accessibility, and
turning on the inspector,


230
00:11:56,776 --> 00:11:58,636
and you will notice that it
brings up this beautiful window


231
00:11:58,956 --> 00:12:01,206
that answers those six questions
we have been talking about.


232
00:12:01,566 --> 00:12:04,066
So you can quickly spot check
the elements in your app


233
00:12:04,066 --> 00:12:06,796
and make sure they are
responding as you expect.


234
00:12:07,296 --> 00:12:11,676
The best way to check
for accessibility is


235
00:12:11,786 --> 00:12:14,306
to use the accessibility
features on the device,


236
00:12:14,636 --> 00:12:16,396
like VoiceOver and
Switch Control.


237
00:12:17,366 --> 00:12:19,746
And I would love to
do that with you now.


238
00:12:20,726 --> 00:12:24,296
So back in Settings, we can turn
on VoiceOver by going to the top


239
00:12:24,296 --> 00:12:28,366
of Accessibility Settings, but
I would recommend if you are new


240
00:12:28,366 --> 00:12:33,136
to VoiceOver to come down to the
Accessibility shortcut and turn


241
00:12:33,136 --> 00:12:36,276
on VoiceOver, so that way you
